    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-26T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-26T13:00:00-05:00" n="614"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d614">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.1431/125: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">O’Donoghue</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-26T12:00:00-06:00"
                            >August 26, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>40. Department’s telegrams numbers 24, August 22, 6 p.m., and 25 August 22, 7
                    p.m. Consul General and I have just seen Minister of Hacienda and left a
                    memorandum based upon telegrams under reference.</p>
                <p>We gather that some minor concessions may be granted but any reduction in wheat
                    flour duty will be difficult if not impossible to obtain. Minister stated he
                    would give immediate attention to our memorandum and that he hoped to reply
                    thereto by September 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">O’Donoghue</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
